ngland"},"cs":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"en":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Taylor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: occupational name for a tailor, from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>taillour</i> ‘tailor’ (Old French <i>tailleor</i>, <i>tailleur</i>; Late Latin <i>taliator</i>, from <i>taliare</i> ‘to cut’). The surname is extremely common in Britain and Ireland. In North America, it has absorbed equivalents from other languages, many of which are also common among Ashkenazic Jews, for example German   Schneider   and Hungarian   Szabo  . It is also very common among African Americans.","In some cases also an Americanized form of French   Terrien   ‘owner of a farmland’ or of its altered forms, such as   Therrien   and   Terrian  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tayloe","meanings":["Altered form of English, Scottish, and Irish   Taylor  ."]},{"name":"Schneider","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Franz, Erwin, Fritz, Dieter, Manfred, Heinz, Alois, Ewald, Helmut.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a tailor, literally ‘cutter’, from Middle High German <i>snīder</i>, German <i>Schneider</i>, Yiddish <i>shnayder</i>. The same term was sometimes used to denote a woodcutter. This surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Hungary, Poland, and Czechia. In Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia it is also established in Slavicized forms (see 2 below). In part, <i>Schneider</i> is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  ). Compare   Sneider   1,   Snider   1, and   Snyder   1.","Germanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Šnajdr</b> or <b>Šnajder</b>, and Czech <b>Šneidr</b>, <b>Šneider</b>, <b>Šnejdr</b>, and <b>Šnejder</b>, surnames of German origin (see above)."]},{"name":"Tayler","meanings":["English: variant of   Taylor  ."]},{"name":"Tailor","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Pravin, Dilip, Mahesh, Sanjay, Kanchan, Kaushik, Manilal, Mohanlal, Navnit, Shailesh, Ajay, Alpana.","Indian (Gujarat and Mumbai): mainly Parsi occupational name from the English word <i>tailor</i>.","English: variant of   Taylor  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Taylor was born in 1380, in Cornwood, Devon, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Bazley. He died in 1450, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Taylor est né en 1380, à Cornwood, Devon, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Elizabeth Bazley. Il est décédé en 1450, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 70 ans."},"de":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Cornwood, Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England","lifeSummary":"William Taylor wurde 1380 in Cornwood, Devon, England geboren. Er hatte mit Elizabeth Bazley mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb 1450 im Alter von 70 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1380–1450":"1380–1450","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1405–1475":"1405–1475","1475":"1475","1